dothelial cells [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2148_23-T4b" ref-type="table">Table 4</xref>b] of the samples [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2148_23-F4" ref-type="fig">Fig. 4</xref>a] and controls [<xref rid="IJO.IJO_2148_23-F4" ref-type="fig">Fig. 4</xref>b], with no statistical difference between the two groups, with <italic toggle="yes">P</italic> = 1.000 for the epithelial staining and <italic toggle="yes">P</italic> = 0.637 for endothelial staining.</p><fig position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2148_23-F4"><label>Figure 4</label><caption><p>(a) IHC analysis of VEGF in both epithelial (green arrow) and endothelial cells (black arrow) at 200&#x000d7;. (b) IHC staining showing weak staining in epithelial and endothelial cells</p></caption><graphic xlink:href="IJO-72-448-g004" position="float"/></fig><table-wrap position="float" id="IJO.IJO_2148_23-T4a"><label>Table 4a</label><caption><p>Comparison of VEGF positivity in epithelial cells. Cells showing both epithelial and endothelial positivity have been excluded from the table</p></caption><table frame="hsides" rules="groups"><thead><tr><th align="center" rowspan="2" colspan="1">Epithelial cell positivity</th><th align="center" rowspan="2" colspan="1"/><th align="center" colspan="3" rowspan="1">Case<hr/></th><th align="center" rowspan="2" colspan="1"/><th align="center" colspan="3" rowspan="1">Control<hr/></th></tr><tr><th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">
